                        "name": "Andrew Jeffery",
                        "email": "andrew@codeconstruct.com.au",
                        "username": "amboar"
                    },
                    "message": "I assume the list is valid from any state, not just the current state?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/State/Host.interface.yaml",
                    "line": 21,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrew Geissler",
                        "email": "geissonator@yahoo.com",
                        "username": "geissonator"
                    },
                    "message": "Yep, let me know if you'd like that specifically called out in this text."
                },
                {
                    "file": "yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/State/Host.interface.yaml",
                    "line": 21,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrew Jeffery",
                        "email": "andrew@codeconstruct.com.au",
                        "username": "amboar"
                    },
                    "message": "I think it's worth stating the intent in the text, given some systems already have constraints on the transitions (i.e. some are unsupported). It's not clear to me that \"supported, but not from states X\" isn't a constraint that might be used though."
                },
                {
                    "file": "yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/State/Host.interface.yaml",
                    "line": 21,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Andrew Geissler",
                        "email": "geissonator@yahoo.com",
                        "username": "geissonator"
                    },
                    "message": "I see, the policy in PSM at least has been to just be a passthrough to systemd targets so if someone wants to power off the system 4 times in a row, they can. So I don't envision this property being something that for example dynamically removes the Off option when the host state is off. This property is just what's allowed at a static system level. I updated the text."
                }
            ],
